{"title_page": "Elizabeth Bartholet", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elizabeth Bartholet\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Civil rights and family law, specializing in child welfare, adoption and reproductive technology, homeschooling opponent.\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = [[Radcliffe College]]<br/>[[Harvard Law School]]\n| employer           = Harvard Law School\n| occupation         = \n| title              = Morris Wasserstein Public Interest Professor of Law, Harvard Law School; Founding Faculty Director Harvard Law School's Child Advocacy Program\n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| boards             = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Elizabeth Bartholet''' is the Morris Wasserstein Public Interest [[Professor of Law]] at [[Harvard Law School]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hls.harvard.edu/faculty/directory/10048/Bartholet|title=Elizabeth Bartholet {{!}} Harvard Law School|last=School|first=Harvard Law|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> and Faculty Director of Harvard Law School's Child Advocacy Program (CAP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cap.law.harvard.edu|title=CAP website|date=2015-07-02|website=Child Advocacy Program|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> She teaches [[civil rights]] and [[family law]], specializing in child welfare, adoption and reproductive technology.\n\nBefore joining the Harvard Faculty, she was engaged in civil rights and public interest work, first with the [[NAACP Legal Defense Fund]], and later as founder and director of the Legal Action Center, a non-profit organization in [[New York City]] focused on [[criminal justice]] and [[substance abuse]] issues.\n\nBartholet is a supporter of the #MeToo movement, but has criticized some of its excesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/1/16/bartholet-metoo-excesses/|title=#MeToo Excesses {{!}} Opinion {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> \n\nBartholet is an outspoken opponent of the homeschooling movement and has urged governments to implement policies to make it more difficult or impossible for parents to educate their children at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2020/05/right-now-risks-homeschooling|title=The Risks of Homeschooling|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author= Elizabeth Bartholet|date=2020 |title=Homeschooling: Parent Rights Absolutism vs. Child Rights to Education & Protection |url=https://arizonalawreview.org/homeschooling-parent-rights-absolutism-vs-child-rights-to-education-protection/ |journal=Arizona Law Review |volume=62 |issue=1 |pages=1 |doi= |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Bartholet characterizes homeschooling parents as \u2018extreme religious ideologues\u2019 who question science (i.e. adopt a skeptical approach to questions of evolution and human impact on climate). A large majority of homeschooling families are conservative [[Christians]] who hold to a traditional, biblically-informed view of morality. Many homeschooling parents consequently attempt to shield their children from what they see as amoral, relativistic, or degenerate contemporary moral philosophy, and because of this alleged insularity Bartholet advocates forced assimilation of this population into what she calls \"mainstream culture\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/harvard-professor-wants-a-presumptive-ban-on-homeschooling-claims-it-promotes-white-supremacy|title=Harvard Professor Wants A \u2018Presumptive Ban\u2018 On Homeschooling, Claims It Promotes White Supremacy|work=[[Daily Wire]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Bartholet was an organizer of the Harvard Summit to Discuss Regulating Homeschooling to be held at the Harvard Law School on June 18-19, 2020. Her co-organizer, William and Mary law professor James Dwyer, is the author of a 1994 law review article entitled \u201cParents\u2019 Religion and Children\u2019s Welfare: Debunking the Doctrine of Parents\u2019 Rights\u201d (82 Calif. L. Rev. 1371), claiming that the fundamental civic relationship is not that between parents and children (the nuclear family) but between the individual and the state. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/hs/state/ma/20200324-harvard-summit-to-discuss-regulating-homeschooling.aspx|title=Harvard Summit to Discuss Regulating Homeschooling|work=[[HSLDA]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] outbreak in 2020, when school closures forced necessary homeschooling<ref>https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/heather-creekmore-how-to-make-homeschooling-work-for-you</ref>, her previously published perspective on homeschooling<ref>https://arizonalawreview.org/pdf/62-1/62arizlrev1.pdf</ref> received attention in Harvard Magazine\u2019s May-June 2020 issue in an article by Erin O\u2019Donnel<ref>https://harvardmagazine.com/2020/05/right-now-risks-homeschooling</ref>, Bartholet's views received media attention <ref>https://www.foxnews.com/us/harvard-homeschool-article-dangerous-parents-risk</ref> and drew criticism from religious sources<ref>https://www.christianpost.com/news/harvard-prof-calls-for-ban-on-homeschooling-responses-emerge.html</ref><ref>https://albertmohler.com/2020/04/20/briefing-4-20-20</ref>, as well as from fellow Harvard Law graduates<ref>https://fee.org/articles/harvard-magazine-calls-for-a-presumptive-ban-on-homeschooling-here-are-5-things-it-got-wrong/</ref><ref>https://medium.com/@melbapearson/a-response-to-the-risks-of-homeschooling-from-a-homeschooled-harvard-grad-67648f9a0d0f</ref><ref>https://www.facebook.com/harrisjalex/posts/3073031376086788?__tn__=H-R</ref>. \n\nBartholet's publications include: Nobody's Children: Abuse and Neglect, Foster Drift, and the Adoption Alternative (Beacon Press, 1999), and Family Bonds: Adoption, Infertility, and the New World of Child Production (Beacon Press, 1999), as well as numerous law review articles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/faculty/bartholet/pubs.php|title=HLS : Elizabeth Bartholet: Publications|website=www.law.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> \n\n\nBartholet has won several awards for her writing and her related advocacy work in the area of adoption and child welfare.{{Citation needed|reason=awards not documented|date=April 2020}} Bartholet received a \u201cMedia Achievement Award\u201d in 1994{{Citation needed|reason=who gave this award?|date=April 2020}} and an Alumnae Recognition Award from Radcliffe College in 1997.\n\nBartholet earned a B.A. degree from [[Radcliffe College]] and a J.D. degree from Harvard Law School.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bartholet, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-legal-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elizabeth Bartholet\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Civil rights and family law, specializing in child welfare, adoption and reproductive technology, homeschooling opponent.\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = [[Radcliffe College]]<br/>[[Harvard Law School]]\n| employer           = Harvard Law School\n| occupation         = \n| title              = Morris Wasserstein Public Interest Professor of Law, Harvard Law School; Founding Faculty Director Harvard Law School's Child Advocacy Program\n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| boards             = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Elizabeth Bartholet''' is the Morris Wasserstein Public Interest [[Professor of Law]] at [[Harvard Law School]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hls.harvard.edu/faculty/directory/10048/Bartholet|title=Elizabeth Bartholet {{!}} Harvard Law School|last=School|first=Harvard Law|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> and Faculty Director of Harvard Law School's Child Advocacy Program (CAP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cap.law.harvard.edu|title=CAP website|date=2015-07-02|website=Child Advocacy Program|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> She teaches [[civil rights]] and [[family law]], specializing in child welfare, adoption and reproductive technology.\n\nBefore joining the Harvard Faculty, she was engaged in civil rights and public interest work, first with the [[NAACP Legal Defense Fund]], and later as founder and director of the Legal Action Center, a non-profit organization in [[New York City]] focused on [[criminal justice]] and [[substance abuse]] issues.\n\nBartholet is a supporter of the #MeToo movement, but has criticized some of its excesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/1/16/bartholet-metoo-excesses/|title=#MeToo Excesses {{!}} Opinion {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> \n\nBartholet is an outspoken opponent of the homeschooling movement and has urged governments to implement policies to make it more difficult or impossible for parents to educate their children at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2020/05/right-now-risks-homeschooling|title=The Risks of Homeschooling|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author= Elizabeth Bartholet|date=2020 |title=Homeschooling: Parent Rights Absolutism vs. Child Rights to Education & Protection |url=https://arizonalawreview.org/homeschooling-parent-rights-absolutism-vs-child-rights-to-education-protection/ |journal=Arizona Law Review |volume=62 |issue=1 |pages=1 |doi= |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Bartholet characterizes homeschooling parents as \u2018extreme religious ideologues\u2019 who question science (i.e. adopt a skeptical approach to questions of evolution and human impact on climate). A large majority of homeschooling families are conservative [[Christians]] who hold to a traditional, biblically-informed view of morality. Many homeschooling parents consequently attempt to shield their children from what they see as amoral, relativistic, or degenerate contemporary moral philosophy, and because of this alleged insularity Bartholet advocates forced assimilation of this population into what she calls \"mainstream culture\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/harvard-professor-wants-a-presumptive-ban-on-homeschooling-claims-it-promotes-white-supremacy|title=Harvard Professor Wants A \u2018Presumptive Ban\u2018 On Homeschooling, Claims It Promotes White Supremacy|work=[[Daily Wire]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Bartholet was an organizer of the Harvard Summit to Discuss Regulating Homeschooling to be held at the Harvard Law School on June 18-19, 2020. Her co-organizer, William and Mary law professor James Dwyer, is the author of a 1994 law review article entitled \u201cParents\u2019 Religion and Children\u2019s Welfare: Debunking the Doctrine of Parents\u2019 Rights\u201d (82 Calif. L. Rev. 1371), claiming that the fundamental civic relationship is not that between parents and children (the nuclear family) but between the individual and the state. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/hs/state/ma/20200324-harvard-summit-to-discuss-regulating-homeschooling.aspx|title=Harvard Summit to Discuss Regulating Homeschooling|work=[[HSLDA]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBartholet's publications include: Nobody's Children: Abuse and Neglect, Foster Drift, and the Adoption Alternative (Beacon Press, 1999), and Family Bonds: Adoption, Infertility, and the New World of Child Production (Beacon Press, 1999), as well as numerous law review articles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/faculty/bartholet/pubs.php|title=HLS : Elizabeth Bartholet: Publications|website=www.law.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> \n\n\nBartholet has won several awards for her writing and her related advocacy work in the area of adoption and child welfare.{{Citation needed|reason=awards not documented|date=April 2020}} Bartholet received a \u201cMedia Achievement Award\u201d in 1994{{Citation needed|reason=who gave this award?|date=April 2020}} and an Alumnae Recognition Award from Radcliffe College in 1997.\n\nBartholet earned a B.A. degree from [[Radcliffe College]] and a J.D. degree from Harvard Law School.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bartholet, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Year of birth mi