mall><ref name=\"Episode 3\"/>\n |WW |April 9, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 3\"/>\n |WW |April 10, 2014 <small>(iOS)</small>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 4 |{{Video game release\n |WW |May 27, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 4\">{{cite web |last=DeMat |first=DeMat |url=http://www.destructoid.com/episode-4-of-the-wolf-among-us-will-fix-this-starting-may-27-275229.phtml |title=Episode 4 of The Wolf Among Us will fix this starting May 27 |date=2014-05-22 |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=2014-05-22 }}</ref>\n |NA |May 27, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n |WW |May 28, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n |WW |May 29, 2014 <small>(IOS)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/> |EU |June 4, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 5 |{{Video game release\n |WW |July 8, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 5\">{{cite web |last=Mahardy |first=Mike |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/07/03/the-wolf-among-us-finale-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us Finale Release Date Announced |date=2014-07-03 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2014-07-03 }}</ref>\n |NA |July 8, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |EU |July 9, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |WW |July 9, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |WW |July 10, 2014 <small>(iOS)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Retail version |{{vgrelease\n |NA |November 4, 2014\n |EU |November 7, 2014\n}} }}\n}}\n| genre = [[Graphic adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Wolf Among Us''''' is an [[Episodic video game|episodic]] [[graphic adventure game]] based on [[Bill Willingham]]'s [[Fables (comics)|''Fables'' comic book series]].<ref name=\"Fables announcement\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2011/02/telltale-games-walking-dead-fables |title=Telltale Games Snags Walking Dead, Fables |date=2011-02-18 |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=2012-05-07 }}</ref> It is developed by [[Telltale Games]]. It is [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] with the comic book universe and is set as a [[prequel]] to the comic book.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=33523 |title=CCI: \"Fables\" Creators Panel Recap |date=2011-07-24 |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=2012-05-07 }}</ref> The game consists of five episodes that were released throughout 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yoon |first=Andrew |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/80745/the-wolf-among-us-season-begins-early-october-spans-five |title=The Wolf Among Us season begins early October, spans five episodes |date=2013-08-20 |publisher=[[Shacknews]] |accessdate=2013-09-17 }}</ref> Retail versions for the [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Xbox 360]], and [[Xbox One]] consoles were released in November 2014.<ref name=\"xbox1 & ps4\">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/telltalegames/status/529694616644120576 |title=Critically-acclaimed #TheWolfAmongUs is now available on @Xbox One and @PlayStation 4, via download and at retail! |date=2014-11-04 |work=Twitter |publisher=Telltale Games |accessdate=2016-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n''The Wolf Among Us'' has been generally well received by critics and garnered a [[cult following]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.desiblitz.com/content/wolf-among-us-remains-telltales-best-game |title=Why The Wolf Among Us Remains Telltale's Best Game |work=Desiblitz |accessdate=August 13, 2017 }}</ref> In July 2017, Telltale announced that a season 2 of ''The Wolf Among Us'' was scheduled for release in 2018. However, Telltale eventually had to shut down for financial reasons in 2018, with its assets being acquired by [[LCG Entertainment]]. One of the first original games from this new company, [[doing business as]] Telltale Games, will be ''The Wolf Among Us 2'', announced in December 2019.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:TWAU Screenshot.png|thumb|250px|left|In-game conversations are presented in the form of dialogue trees]]\n''The Wolf Among Us'' is a [[graphic adventure game]], played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]].<ref name=\"Gameplanet Review\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Chris |url=http://www.gameplanet.com.au/pc/reviews/g525f3b1c9b3f2/The-Wolf-Among-Us-Episode-1-Faith-review/?referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1: Faith review |date=October 17, 2013 |work=[[Gameplanet]] |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> The player controls protagonist [[Bigby Wolf]], who must investigate the murder of a woman.<ref name=\"PCGamer Preview\">{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Hollander |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/the-wolf-among-us-preview |title=The Wolf Among Us preview |date=August 27, 2013 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> Throughout the game, the player explores various [[3D computer graphics|three-dimensional]] environments, such as apartment buildings and a bar.<ref name=\"TT Review\">{{cite web |last=Gronli |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.technologytell.com/gaming/118966/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-review-bringing-fables-to-life |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1 Review: Bringing Fables to life |date=October 21, 2013 |work=Technology Tell |publisher=NAPCO Media |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> When exploring an environment, the player may find an object they can interact with; when this occurs, they must move a [[Cursor (user interface)|cursor]] over the object to select and examine it.<ref name=\"Polygon Review\">{{cite web |last=McElroy |first=Justin |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/10/10/4824252/fables-the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode One: Faith Review: At The Door |date=October 10, 2013 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> Items of interest are stored in an inventory, and can be used later in the story.<ref name=\"Destructoid Review\"/> The player may also talk with [[non-player character]]s, and see the conversations presented in the form of [[dialogue tree]]s.<ref name=\"Polygon Article\">{{cite web |last=Corriea |first=Alexa Ray |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/4/9/5594270/the-female-gaze-how-being-watched-affects-morality-in-adventure-games |title=The female gaze: how being watched affects your morality in adventure games |date=April 9, 2014 |work=Polygon |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> The dialogue options chosen during conversations would either have a positive or negative effect on how other characters view Bigby, and their perceptions would influence future events in the story.<ref name=\"Destructoid Review\">{{cite web |last=Aziz |first=Hamza |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wolf-among-us-faith-263249.phtml |title=Review: The Wolf Among Us: Faith |date=October 10, 2013 |work=[[Destructoid]] |publisher=Modern Method |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> Some scenes are more action-oriented, forcing the player to respond to a series of [[quick time event]] (QTE) prompts.<ref name=\"GameSpot Review\">{{cite web |last=Watters |first=Chris |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-review-testing-my-fait/1900-6415497 |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 Review - Testing My Faith |date=October 21, 2013 |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> The player is not required to complete every QTE prompt, and skipping certain prompts may affect future events in the story.<ref name=\"TouchArcade Review\">{{cite web |last=Leray |first=Joseph |url=http://toucharcade.com/2014/08/25/the-wolf-among-us-review |title='The Wolf Among Us' Review - Red in Tooth and Claw |date=August 25, 2014 |work=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Setting===\n''The Wolf Among Us'' is set in the year 1986, nearly twenty years before the events of ''[[Fables (comics)|Fables]]''.<ref name=\"GameSpot Full Review\">{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Justin |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-wolf-among-us-review/1900-6415981 |title=The Wolf Among Us Review |work=GameSpot |date=December 5, 2014 |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> For years, many of the magical lands described in myth, legend, and folklore (known as The Homelands) have been occupied by an enigmatic tyrant known as the Adversary.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mejia |first=Ozzie |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/81575/the-characters-of-the-wolf-among-us-and-where-the |title=The characters of The Wolf Among Us and where the story may go next |date=October 16, 2013 |work=[[Shacknews]] |publisher=Gamerhub |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> To escape the Adversary's totalitarian regime, many of The Homelands inhabitants fled to [[colonial America]], and created an enclave known as [[Fabletown]], now located in modern-day [[Manhattan]]. To mask their presence from the native humans, all non-human fables have to purchase an enchantment known as a \"glamour\" which allows them to appear human, or be relocated to a rural community known as \"The Farm\".\n\n===Characters===\n{{see also|List of Fables characters}}\nThe protagonist of ''The Wolf Among Us'' is Bigby Wolf ([[Adam Harrington (voice actor)|Adam Harrington]]), formerly the [[Big Bad Wolf]]. He is the sheriff of Fabletown, currently working at the \"Business Office\" under corrupt interim mayor [[Ichabod Crane]] ([[Roger L. Jackson]]), aided by [[Snow White (Fables)|Snow White]] ([[Erin Yvette]]) and the [[Magic Mirror (Snow White)|Magic Mirror]] ([[Gavin Hammon]]) in his investigation along with the help of Bufkin the [[Winged monkeys|winged monkey]] (Chuck Kourouklis) that manages Fabletown's records. Aristocrat [[Bluebeard]] ([[Dave Fennoy]]) also works at the Office though his motives are unclear. Bigby resides at the Woodlands apartments where Colin (Brian Sommer), one of the [[Three Little Pigs]], occasionally crashes at his place. [[Beauty and the Beast]] ([[Melissa Hutchison]] and Gavin Hammon) are also residents of the Woodlands, though currently struggling with a troubled marriage. One of the Fables that Bigby frequently contacts is [[Mr. Toad]] (Chuck Kourouklis) and his son TJ (Toad Jr.), who live in a run-down apartment building nearby.\n\nIn the first episode, the player is introduced to [[Little Red Riding Hood|The Woodsman]] (Adam Harrington), who lives in the same building as Mr. Toad. Standing in Bigby's way are [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee|Dee and Dum Tweedle]] (Gavin Hammon), twin private investigators and criminals. Bigby also encounters Holly (Janet Lipsey), a [[Troll]] who runs the Trip Trap bar, and  barfly [[Grendel]] ([[Kid Beyond]]). The second episode introduces trickster and thief [[Jack Horner (comics)|Jack Horner]] (Colin Benoit), [[Georgie Porgie]] ([[Kevin Howarth]]), a pimp and the owner of the Pudding & Pie strip club, along with prostitute Nerissa (Molly Benson), the former [[The Little Mermaid|Little Mermaid]], Vivian (Sandy Delonga), and [[Clever Hans (fairy tale)|Clever Hans]] (Ben Knoll), the club's bouncer. The third episode introduces the janitor [[Flycatcher (comics)|Flycatcher]] (Dustin Rubin), [[Bloody Mary (folklore)|Bloody Mary]] ([[Kathryn Cressida]]) as a minion of [[There Was a Crooked Man|the Crooked Man]] (Philip Banks), and Aunty Greenleaf ([[Laura Bailey (voice actress)|Laura Bailey]]), a rogue witch who illegally sells cheap black-market glamours to Fables. The fourth episode introduces the [[Jersey Devil]] (Bobby Vickers), the manager of the Lucky Pawn shop and [[Rub-a-dub-dub|Johann the butcher]] ([[Terry McGovern (actor)|Terry McGovern]]), the former owner of the Cut Above butcher shop who has been forced out of his business by the Crooked Man's henchmen.\n\n===Plot===\nThis is a broad overview of the plot. Certain decisions made by the player will alter details of specific events.\n\nBigby Wolf, formerly the Big Bad Wolf, is the Sheriff of Fabletown, a hidden community of fairytale characters located in 1980s New York City. Receiving a call from Mr. Toad, Bigby protects a prostitute from an intoxicated Woodsman. Before she departs, she tells him he is not as bad as everyone says he is.\n\nLater that night, Bigby and Snow White find the woman's head left on the Woodlands doorstep. Clues left with the head identify her as Faith, a Fable from ''[[Allerleirauh]]''. Deputy Mayor Ichabod Crane orders him and Snow to investigate her death. They head to the apartment she shared with her husband Prince Lawrence and find the [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee|Tweedles]], Dee and Dum, snooping through it. They learn that Lawrence and Faith struggled to make ends meet and Faith took up prostitution to help pay the bills. Bigby leaves Snow at the Woodlands while he continues to trace leads. When he returns, he finds the Woodlands surrounded by police, Snow's head sitting on the building's steps.\n\nBigby is taken in for questioning by the mundy police, but Crane uses a spell to wipe the incident from the police's minds. When they return, they are surprised to find Snow still alive; the head is shown to be disguised by a black-market glamour, a spell that non-human Fables use, and belongs instead to a troll named Lily. Bigby tracks Lily's connections to the Pudding & Pie, a strip club run by Georgie Porgie, but Georgie claims innocence. One of his other prostitutes, Nerissa, cryptically directs Bigby to a nearby hotel room. There he finds Lily's blood on the bed, and photographic evidence of Crane engaging in sexual acts with Lily glamoured to look like Snow. He informs Snow of this, and they race back to the Woodlands to find Crane gone, and the Magic Mirror, which could have revealed his location, shattered with one shard missing.\n\nBigby follows a trail of clues to Crane's whereabouts to the apartment of Aunty Greenleaf, one of the witches that makes the black-market glamours. Along the way, Bigby discovers that Crane has been embezzling money from Fabletown over the years to pay off a loan shark known as the Crooked Man. Greenleaf points the two back to the Pudding & Pie. Storming the club, they find Crane trying to extract information out of the prostitutes to prove his innocence. Snow realizes Crane's actions are not that of a murderer, and he is arrested for his embezzlement. Leaving the club, they are attacked by the Crooked Man and his henchmen, the Tweedles and Bloody Mary. Mary and the Tweedles goad Bigby into his werewolf form, and a fight breaks out. When Mary critically wounds Bigby with a silver bullet, Snow steps in to stop the fight and willingly gives up Crane to the Crooked Man to save Bigby's life.\n\nBack at the Woodlands, Bigby struggles to find clues when Nerissa appears. He realizes the ribbon she wears prevents her from speaking the truth, that Faith wore an identical ribbon, and that she died when the ribbon was removed. He follows another trail of clues, and finds evidence of the black-market glamour ring in the Cut Above butcher shop, a pawn shop called the Lucky Pawn where the Crooked Man distributes his loans to Fables owned by Jersey Devil, another henchman of the Crooked Man, and Crane's presence, as well as the missing Mirror Shard. The Mirror reveals Mary putting Crane onto an overseas flight to Paris to keep him from talking, as well as the next location of the door to the Crooked Man's lair, which moves around the city.\n\nBigby enters the Crooked Man's lair alone, meeting him and his agents. The Crooked Man reveals Georgie as Faith and Lily's killer and claims he misunderstood his orders to deal with them, but Georgie asserts the Crooked Man told him to kill the women. A fight ensues and the Crooked Man and a fatally stabbed Georgie escape. When Bigby pursues Georgie and his lover Vivian to the Pudding & Pie, she explains that the Crooked Man and Georgie were acting to stop a plot spearheaded by Faith with the other prostitutes to escape their forced servitude. Vivian is revealed to be the girl with the ribbon around her neck and, having made copies of her ribbon, trapped women like Faith, Lily, and Nerissa for Georgie whilst guaranteeing their silence. Regretting her actions, Vivian undoes her ribbon, breaking the spell but severing her head.\n\nBigby then finds the Crooked Man hiding in an old foundry, and after turning into his true wolf form to kill Bloody Mary, corners him in an office, where he demands a fair trial at the Woodlands. Bigby returns to the Witching Well at the Business Office to recount events to the assembled Fables of the Woodlands, where he and Snow are forced to defend their actions against claims from the Fables. Bigby recounts Vivian's and Georgie's confessions regarding the Crooked Man's involvement, but his word is deemed untrustworthy. Nerissa appears and testifies that she and five other women heard the Crooked Man order the murders. Their testimonies are considered sufficient to believe what Bigby did was right.\n\nIn the epilogue, Snow becomes the new Deputy Mayor and deals with the fallout of the Crooked Man's actions, while Bigby sees off the Fables being taken back to the Farm. Afterward, he encounters Nerissa, who is moving on with her life. She admits that Faith concocted a plan with her and Lily to blackmail Georgie and the Crooked Man for their freedom, using a picture of Lily and Crane together, but Georgie killed the two women when she panicked and revealed their plot to him. Nerissa left Faith's head at the Woodlands to get Bigby involved, and gave false testimony to have the Crooked Man punished, knowing that he was the one who ordered their deaths. Leaving, she comments that Bigby is not as bad as everyone says he is, causing Bigby to recall Faith saying the same before her death. Several past conversations with Faith and Nerissa play out in Bigby's head, leading him to question the true identity of Nerissa.\n\n==Episodes==\nEpisodic releases for the Microsoft Windows, Xbox 360, OS X and PlayStation 3 platforms were released near-simultaneously within the same week; the iOS and PlayStation Vita episodic releases were expected to trail these by about a month or so.\n{{Episode table|background=#142F26|overall=|title=|director=|writer=|airdate=|released=y\n|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = Faith\n |DirectedBy = Nick Herman and Dennis Lenart\n |WrittenBy = Pierre Shorette\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2013|10|11}}\n |ShortSummary = The first murder of a Fable in several years leads Bigby on the trail of a killer.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |Title = Smoke and Mirrors\n |DirectedBy = Jason Latino\n |WrittenBy = [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]], Adam Hines, and Nicole Martinez\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|4}}\n |ShortSummary = Bigby continues investigating for the 'serial killer' walking the streets of Fabletown. He also attempts to find answers from Faith's pimp: Georgie Porgie, and becomes more involved with Beauty and Beast's affairs.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |Title = A Crooked Mile\n |DirectedBy = Martin Montgomery\n |WrittenBy = Adam Hines and Nicole Martinez\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|4|8}}\n |ShortSummary = Following a shocking revelation, Bigby pursues Ichabod Crane, who is now in hiding.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |Title = In Sheep's Clothing\n |DirectedBy = Kent Mudle\n |WrittenBy = Dan Martin\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|5|27}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Kalmari |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/22/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4-release-date-announced |title=The wolf among us episode 4 release date announced |date=2014-05-22 |accessdate=2014-05-22 |publisher=IGN }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Bigby must delve into the criminal underworld to find the Crooked Man.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |Title = Cry Wolf\n |DirectedBy = Vahram Antonian\n |WrittenBy = Nicole Martinez and Adam Hines\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|7|8}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Matulef |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-07-03-the-wolf-among-us-first-season-concludes-next-week |title=The Wolf Among Us' first season concludes next week |date=2014-07-03 |accessdate=2014-07-03 |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Secrets are revealed and decisions are made as Bigby squares off against the Crooked Man, facing off against his deadliest agent, Bloody Mary and learns the full truth about his crimes against Fabletown.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n}}\n\n==Development==\nIn 2011, [[Telltale Games]] announced that it had acquired licenses to develop video games based on two comic book series, ''[[The Walking Dead (comic book)|The Walking Dead]]'' by [[Robert Kirkman]], and ''[[Fables (comic book)|Fables]]'' by [[Bill Willingham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20110217/telltale-signs-that-videogames-will-be-downloaded-not-sold-at-retail/?mod=ATD_skybox |title=Telltale Signs That Videogames Will Be Downloaded, Not Sold At Retail |date=2011-02-17 |publisher=[[All Things Digital]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2011/07/21/bill-willingham-to-work-on-telltales-fables |title=Bill Willingham to work on Telltale's Fables? |date=2011-02-17 |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref> This announcement came around the same time that the television series [[The Walking Dead (TV series)|''The Walking Dead'']] became critically successful, leading to Telltale to put much of their initial focus on developing ''The Walking Dead'' property through 2011 and 2012.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\">{{cite web |last=Byrne |first=Katherine |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/the-wolf-among-us-was-almost-unshippable-and-could-have-been-a-comedy-says-telltale/0187154 |title=The Wolf Among Us was 'almost unshippable' and could have been a comedy, says Telltale |date=September 18, 2017 |work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] |accessdate=September 18, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921013007/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/the-wolf-among-us-was-almost-unshippable-and-could-have-been-a-comedy-says-telltale/0187154# |archive-date=2017-09-21 }}</ref> This game was released by April 2012, and was a critical success for Telltale. With ''The Walking Dead'' shipping, the company then started working on their ''Fables'' title, but according to Telltale's Job Stauffer, they struggled with the narrative of the title over a year and a half. Stauffer said at one point, they found the game to be more of a comedy, but without much humorous substance and in an un-shippable state.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/> Stauffer said that their team rallied together to refocus the game, delaying it from an early 2012 release<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/02/18/telltales-first-fables-episode-due-in-q1-2012 |title=Telltale's first Fables episode due in Q1 2012 |date=2011-02-18 |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=2012-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017074855/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/02/18/telltales-first-fables-episode-due-in-q1-2012 |archive-date=2013-10-17 }}</ref> to late 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/12/fables-wont-tell-tales-until-q3-2012 |title=Fables won't tell tales until Q3 2012 |date=2012-03-12 |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=2012-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017022435/http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/12/fables-wont-tell-tales-until-q3-2012 |archive-date=2013-10-17 }}</ref> and ultimately to October 2013 when it finally shipped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mixnmojo.com/news/The-Wolf-Among-Us-Reportedly-Delayed-Until-Fall-2013 |title=The Wolf Among Us Reportedly Delayed Until Fall 2013 |date=2013-08-21 |publisher=[[The International House of Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-10-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"polygon pre-order\"/> This did allow for Telltale to incorporate mechanics that had proven successful in ''The Walking Dead'' into their ''Fables'' game.<ref name=\"after TWD\"/>\n\nDue to these delays, Telltale re-announced the ''Fables'' game at the [[New York Comic Con]] in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/telltale-confirms-fables-game-6398311 |title=Telltale Confirms Fables Game |date=2012-10-15 |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref> The name ''The Wolf Among Us'' was revealed in March 2013, and is based on the main character Bigby Wolf.<ref name=\"Fables announcement\"/><ref name=\"after TWD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/12/whats-next-for-telltale-games |title=What's Next for Telltale Games? |date=2013-02-12 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2013-02-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/27/telltales-fables-is-called-the-wolf-among-us |title=Telltale\u2019s Fables is Called The Wolf Among Us |author=Andrew Goldfarb |date=March 27, 2013 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2019-12-19 |archive-url=https://archive.is/y1NiI |archive-date=2013-08-16 }}</ref>\n\nPre-orders were made available October 3, 2013 from Telltale Games and Steam. Those who pre-ordered through Telltale received a collector's DVD at the end of the season.<ref name=\"polygon pre-order\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/10/3/4801198/the-wolf-among-us-available-for-pre-order-out-this-month |title=The Wolf Among Us available for pre-order, out this month |date=2013-10-03 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2013-10-08 }}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe game was initially released across five episodes between October 2013 and July 2014 for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3, and Xbox 360 platforms.\n\n===Release announcements and dates===\n{{plainlist|\n*On October 8, 2013, it was announced that ''The Wolf Among Us'' would be released on Xbox 360, PC, and Mac worldwide on October 11th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/10/08/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1 Release Date Announced |date=2013-10-08 |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref>\n*On October 11, 2013, the digital download released worldwide for [[Xbox 360]], and for [[Microsoft Windows]] from the Telltale Games store.<ref name=\"PC and OS X release\"/> It was also announced that it would release on [[PlayStation 3]] on October 15th in North America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dccomics.com/blog/2018/10/30/the-wolf-among-us-season-premiere-now-available-from-telltale-games-and-dc |title='The Wolf Among Us' Season Premiere Now Available from Telltale Games and DC Entertainment |date=2013-10-11 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref>\n*On October 14, 2013, the digital download released worldwide for [[OS X]] from the Telltale Games store, after fixing an issue with the October 11th release build.<ref name=\"PC and OS X release\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/10/11/the-wolf-among-us-encounters-mac-problems-telltale-working-on-fix.aspx |title=Update: The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 Now Available For Mac |date=2013-10-15 |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=2013-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101075026/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/10/11/the-wolf-among-us-encounters-mac-problems-telltale-working-on-fix.aspx |archive-date=2013-11-01 }}</ref> It also became available through Steam for both PC and Mac.\n*On October 15, 2013, the digital download released on [[PlayStation 3]] in North America<ref name=\"Episode 1\"/> and on October 16, 2013 in Europe and Australia.<ref name=\"PS3PAL\"/>\n*On October 24, 2013, it was announced that it would release on [[iOS]] and [[PlayStation Vita]] in the Fall.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tach |first=Dave |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/10/24/5024832/the-wolf-among-ios-ps-vita |title=The Wolf Among Us headed to iOS and PS Vita this fall |date=2013-10-24 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2014-07-18 }}</ref> The [[iOS]] version was released worldwide on December 4, 2013.<ref name=\"iOS\"/>\n*On February 10, 2014, it was announced that it would release on [[PlayStation Vita]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dunning |first=Jason |url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2014/02/10/playstation-vita-to-get-over-100-games-in-2014 |title=PlayStation Vita to Get \"Over 100 Games\" in 2014: The Wolf Among Us, Invizimals, and More Highlighted |date=February 10, 2014 |work=playstationlifestyle.net |accessdate=April 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n*On May 30, 2014, it was announced that it would release on [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] later that year. Retail versions for [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] were also available for pre-order.<ref>{{cite web |last=Corriea |first=Alexa Rae |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/5/30/5764514/the-walking-dead-wolf-among-us-ps4-xbox-one-telltale-games |title=Telltale's The Walking Dead, The Wolf Among Us coming to PS4 and Xbox One |date=2014-05-30 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2014-05-30 }}</ref>\n*On November 4, 2014, it released on [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], and [[Xbox One]] in North America and November 7, 2014 in Europe at both retail and digital stores. In addition, the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] retail versions also released on those days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.justpushstart.com/2014/10/wolf-us-ps-vitaps4-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us PS Vita/PS4 Release Date Announced |date=2014-10-10 |publisher=Just Push Start |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref><ref name=\"xbox1 & ps4\"/>\n}}\n\n===Sequel===\nWhen ''The Wolf Among Us'' was completed by July 2014, Telltale had thought of doing a second season, but they had already committed to the projects leading to ''[[Tales from the Borderlands]]'', ''[[Minecraft: Story Mode]]'', and ''[[Game of Thrones (2014 video game)|Game of Thrones]]''.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/> The company was aware of strong interest in a second season through the intervening years, and they were looking for the right time to develop it.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/>\n\nA second yet-to-be-named season was announced during the July 2017 [[San Diego Comic Con]], and was originally set to premiere in 2018 for personal computers, consoles, and mobile devices. Both Harrington and Yvette were to return to voice Bigby and Snow White, respectively.<ref name=\"vg247 final season\">{{cite web |last=Nunneley |first=Stephanny |url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/07/19/the-wolf-among-us-2-the-walking-dead-the-final-season-coming-in-2018-batman-the-enemy-within-out-in-august |title=The Wolf Among Us 2, The Walking Dead: The Final Season coming in 2018, Batman: The Enemy Within out in August |date=July 19, 2017 |work=[[VG247]] |accessdate=July 19, 2017 }}</ref> Stauffer said that Season Two would not resolve the apparent cliffhanger related to Nerissa's connection to Faith; he said that it was meant to be ending similar to a [[film noir]] work that made the viewer think about the implications, but never saw this themselves as a cliffhanger. Instead, Season 2 would have continued on with more narrative related to Bigby and Snow White.<ref>{{cite web |last=Purslow |first=Matt |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/the-wolf-among-us/the-wolf-among-us-cliffhanger |title=The Wolf Among Us\u2019s ending is \"absolutely not a cliffhanger\" |date=August 23, 2017 |work=[[PCGamesN]] |accessdate=August 24, 2017 }}</ref>\nBy May 2018, Telltale announced that due to recent internal studio issues, they had to push back the release of the sequel until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last= Kim |first=Matt |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-wolf-among-us-2-delayed-to-2019 |title=The Wolf Among Us 2 Delayed Until 2019 |date=May 25, 2018 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=May 25, 2018 }}</ref> In September 2018, Telltale had a majority studio closure due to \"insurmountable challenges\", cancelling ''The Wolf Among Us''{{' }}s second season among other projects in development.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kim |first=Matt |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/report-telltale-games-shutting-down-the-wolf-among-us-2-and-stranger-things-canceled |title=Sources: Telltale Games Shutting Down, The Wolf Among Us 2 and Stranger Things Canceled [Update, Correction] |date=September 21, 2018 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=September 21, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nUpon Telltale's revival by LCG Entertainment, ''The Wolf Among Us'' was one of the titles reacquired by LCG, but no announcement was made at that time about the sequel.<ref>{{cite web |last=Campbell |first=Colin |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/28/20835854/telltale-games-return-walking-dead-lcg-entertainment |title=Telltale Games is being revived |date=August 28, 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=November 28, 2019 }}</ref> The company announced ''The Wolf Among Us 2'' at [[The Game Awards 2019]]. The sequel will continue events after the first game, though still remain as a prequel to the comic series. The game is being developed in association with [[AdHoc Studio]], formed by former Telltale Games staff, who will focus on the game's narrative and cinematic elements while Telltale will implement the gameplay and other designs. In addition to returning Telltale staff, Harrington and Yvette will return to voice Bigby and Snow White, and Emerson-Johnson will compose music for the game. The game is being developed on the [[Unreal Engine]], and will be released in an episodic approach.<ref>{{cite web |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |\n url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/12/12/telltale-confirms-it-will-make-the-wolf-among-us-2 |title=Telltale confirms it will make The Wolf Among Us 2 |date=\n December 12, 2019 |work=[[Venture Beat]] |accessdate=December 16, 2019 }}</ref> This sequel will be worked completely from scratch, using none of the ideas and initial work that had been done under the former Telltale banner before its closure.<ref>{{cite web |last=Olsen |first=Matthew |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-wolf-among-us-2-is-starting-from-scratch-telltale-confirms |title=The Wolf Among Us 2 is Starting From Scratch, Telltale Confirms |date=December 17, 2019 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=December 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG Series Reviews\n| game1 = The Wolf Among Us\n| mc1 = (PS4) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 80/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref>\n| game2 = Episode 1 \u2013 Faith\n| mc2 = (PS3) 85/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 85/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref><br/>(iOS) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 82/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref>\n| game3 = Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors\n| mc3 = (PS3) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 76/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 73/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/x360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game4 = Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile\n| mc4 = (PS3) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 77/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game5 = Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing\n| mc5 = (PC) 75/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 74/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 69/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game6 = Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf\n| mc6 = (X360) 85/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 84/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 75/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Wolf Among Us'' has received mostly positive reviews from critics. Praise was given to the game's story, action sequences, atmosphere, visual style and faithfulness to the source material while criticism was focused on its pacing and technical issues.\n\n===Episode 1 \u2013 Faith===\n''Episode 1 \u2013 Faith'' received positive reviews from critics. [[Review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]] gave the PlayStation 3 version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP1\"/> the PC version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP1\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 82/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP1\"/>\n\n===Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors===\n''Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors'' received mixed to positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PlayStation 3 version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP2\"/> the PC version 76/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP2\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 73/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP2\"/>\n\n===Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile===\n''Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile'' received positive reviews. Metacritic gave the PlayStation 3 version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP3\"/> the PC version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP3\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 77/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP3\"/>\n\n===Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing===\n''Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing'' received mixed to positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PC version 75/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP4\"/> the Xbox 360 version 74/100,<ref name=\"MCX360EP4\"/> and the PlayStation 3 version 69/100.<ref name=\"MCPS3EP4\"/>\n\n===Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf===\n''Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf'' received positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PC version 84/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP5\"/> the Xbox 360 version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCX360EP5\"/> and the PlayStation 3 version 75/100.<ref name=\"MCPS3EP5\"/>\n\n===Awards===\nThe series was nominated for Outstanding Achievement in Story and Adventure Game of the Year for the 18th Annual D.I.C.E. Awards by the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interactive.org/images/pdfs/18th-Annual-DICE-Finalists.pdf |title=18th Annual D.I.C.E. Awards Finalists |format=PDF |date=January 14, 2015 |publisher=[[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] |accessdate=January 14, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe series was nominated for two 2014 [[British Academy Games Awards|BAFTA Games Awards]] for Story and Performer (Adam Harrington as Bigby Wolf), losing both to ''[[The Last of Us: Left Behind]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2015/games |title=Games in 2015 - BAFTA Awards |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |accessdate=December 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2014 [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] (NAVGTR) awards the game won ''Direction in a Game Cinema'' and received six nominations: ''Writing in a Drama'' (Pierre Shorette), ''Performance in a Drama, Lead'' ([[Adam Harrington (voice actor)|Adam Harrington]]), ''Original Dramatic Score, Franchise'' (Jared Emerson-Johnson), ''Game, Original Adventure'' (Joe Pinney), ''Camera Direction in a Game Engine'' (Dennis Lenart) and ''Art Direction, Contemporary'' (David Bogan).<ref>{{cite web |title=NAVGTR Awards (2014) |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/2445 |website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers }}</ref>\n\n==Comic adaptation==\nAt the 2014 [[New York Comic Con]], [[Vertigo Comics]] announced that they will be adapting ''The Wolf Among Us'' into comic form, to be released digitally first in December 2014 and later as print comic. The story was adapted for the comic by Lilah Sturges, who has previously written for the ''Fables'' series, and Dave Justus, staying otherwise true to the game's story but exploring some of the characters and back story in more depth.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hennon |first=Blake |url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/fables-the-wolf-among-us-matthew-sturges-dave-justus-on-the-case/#/0 |title=\u2018Fables: The Wolf Among Us': Matthew Sturges, Dave Justus on the case |date=2014-10-10 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2014-10-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Pitts |first=Lan |url=http://www.newsarama.com/22958-fables-the-wolf-among-us-writers-tackle-comic-adaptation-of-game-adaptation-of-comic.html |title= FABLES: THE WOLF AMONG US Writers Tackle Comic Adaptation of Game Adaptation of Comic |date=2014-12-11 |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref> The comic has since been completed.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.telltalegames.com/thewolfamongus/ Telltale's ''The Wolf Among Us'' website]\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Telltale Games}}\n{{Fables}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf Among Us, The}}\n[[Category:2013 video games]]\n[[Category:Detective video games]]\n[[Category:Episodic video games]]\n[[Category:Fables (comics)]]\n[[Category:Interactive movie video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Mystery video games]]\n[[Category:Neo-noir video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Vita games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Telltale Games games]]\n[[Category:Video games with cel-shaded animation]]\n[[Category:Video games based on DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jared Emerson-Johnson]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1986]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Video games about werewolves]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Wolf Among Us\n| image = The Wolf Among Us cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Telltale Games]]\n| publisher = Telltale Games\n| director = {{plainlist|\n* Nick Herman\n* Dennis Lenart\n* Jason Latino\n* Martin Montgomery\n* Kent Mudle\n* Vahram Antonian\n }}\n| producer = Chris Schroyer\n| designer = {{plainlist|\n* Ryan Kaufman\n* Joe Pinney\n* Aaron Casillas\n }}\n| programmer = {{plainlist|\n* Keenan Patterson\n* Jason Reis\n* David R. Chaverri\n }}\n| artist = David Bogan\n| writer = {{plainlist|\n* Pierre Shorette\n* [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]]\n* Adam Hines\n* Dan Martin\n* Nicole Martinez\n }}\n| composer = [[Jared Emerson-Johnson]]\n| series = ''[[Fables (comics)|Fables]]''\n| engine = [[Telltale Tool]]\n| platforms = {{plainlist|\n* [[Windows]]\n* [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n* [[iOS]]\n* [[OS X]]\n* [[PlayStation 3]]\n* [[PlayStation 4]]\n* [[PlayStation Vita]]\n* [[Xbox 360]]\n* [[Xbox One]]\n }}\n| released = October 14, 2013<br/>{{plainlist|\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 1 |{{Video game release\n |WW |October 11, 2013<ref name=\"Episode 1\">{{cite web |last=Ivan |first=Tom |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/telltales-wolf-among-us-launches-october-11 |title=The Telltale\u2019s The Wolf Among Us launches on October 11 |date=2013-10-09 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=2014-07-18 }}</ref>\n |WW |October 14, 2013 <small>(OS X)</small><ref name=\"PC and OS X release\">{{cite web |url=http://www.telltalegames.com/community/discussion/50985/release-day-discussion-october-11th-2013 |title=Release day discussion: The PC and Mac version of Episode 1: Faith is now available |publisher=[[Telltale Games]] |date=2013-10-15 |accessdate=2013-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022175649/http://www.telltalegames.com/community/discussion/50985/release-day-discussion-october-11th-2013 |archive-date=2013-10-22 }}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n |NA |October 15, 2013 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 1\"/>\n |EU |October 16, 2013 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"PS3PAL\">{{cite web |last=L |first=Stefan |url=https://www.thesixthaxis.com/2013/10/16/playstation-store-update-161013-the-wolf-among-us-sanctum-2-tlou-dlc |title=PlayStation Store Update: 16/10/13 \u2013 The Wolf Among Us, Sanctum 2 & TLOU DLC |date=2013-10-16 |publisher=The Sixth Axis |accessdate=2013-10-16 }}</ref> |AU |October 16, 2013 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"PS3PAL\"/>\n |WW |December 4, 2013 <small>(iOS)</small><ref name=\"iOS\">{{cite web |last=Liebl |first=Matt |url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/2013/12/04/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-faith-coming-to-ios-devices-today |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1 'Faith' coming to iOS devices today |date=2013-12-04 |publisher=GameZone |accessdate=2013-12-04 }}</ref>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 2 |{{Video game release\n |WW |February 4, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 2\">{{cite web |last=Desat |first=Marla |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/131894-Telltales-The-Wolf-Among-Us-Episode-Two-Arrives-February-4 |title=Telltale's The Wolf Among Us Episode Two Arrives February 4 |date=2014-02-01 |publisher=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |accessdate=2014-02-01 }}</ref>\n |NA |February 4, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 2\"/>\n |EU |February 5, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 2\"/>\n |WW |February 5, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 2\"/>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 3 |{{Video game release\n |WW |April 8, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 3\">{{cite web |last=Mahardy |first=Mike |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/04/02/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3-release-dates-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 3 Release Dates Announced |date=2014-04-02 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2014-04-02 }}</ref> |NA |April 8, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 3\"/> |EU |April 9, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 3\"/>\n |WW |April 9, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 3\"/>\n |WW |April 10, 2014 <small>(iOS)</small>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 4 |{{Video game release\n |WW |May 27, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 4\">{{cite web |last=DeMat |first=DeMat |url=http://www.destructoid.com/episode-4-of-the-wolf-among-us-will-fix-this-starting-may-27-275229.phtml |title=Episode 4 of The Wolf Among Us will fix this starting May 27 |date=2014-05-22 |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=2014-05-22 }}</ref>\n |NA |May 27, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n |WW |May 28, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n |WW |May 29, 2014 <small>(IOS)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/> |EU |June 4, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 4\"/>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Episode 5 |{{Video game release\n |WW |July 8, 2014<ref name=\"Episode 5\">{{cite web |last=Mahardy |first=Mike |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/07/03/the-wolf-among-us-finale-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us Finale Release Date Announced |date=2014-07-03 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2014-07-03 }}</ref>\n |NA |July 8, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |EU |July 9, 2014 <small>(PS3)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |WW |July 9, 2014 <small>(X360)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n |WW |July 10, 2014 <small>(iOS)</small><ref name=\"Episode 5\"/>\n}} }}\n{{collapsible list |title=Retail version |{{vgrelease\n |NA |November 4, 2014\n |EU |November 7, 2014\n}} }}\n}}\n| genre = [[Graphic adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Wolf Among Us''''' is an [[Episodic video game|episodic]] [[graphic adventure game]] based on [[Bill Willingham]]'s [[Fables (comics)|''Fables'' comic book series]].<ref name=\"Fables announcement\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2011/02/telltale-games-walking-dead-fables |title=Telltale Games Snags Walking Dead, Fables |date=2011-02-18 |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=2012-05-07 }}</ref> It is developed by [[Telltale Games]]. It is [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] with the comic book universe and is set as a [[prequel]] to the comic book.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=33523 |title=CCI: \"Fables\" Creators Panel Recap |date=2011-07-24 |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=2012-05-07 }}</ref> The game consists of five episodes that were released throughout 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yoon |first=Andrew |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/80745/the-wolf-among-us-season-begins-early-october-spans-five |title=The Wolf Among Us season begins early October, spans five episodes |date=2013-08-20 |publisher=[[Shacknews]] |accessdate=2013-09-17 }}</ref> Retail versions for the [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Xbox 360]], and [[Xbox One]] consoles were released in November 2014.<ref name=\"xbox1 & ps4\">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/telltalegames/status/529694616644120576 |title=Critically-acclaimed #TheWolfAmongUs is now available on @Xbox One and @PlayStation 4, via download and at retail! |date=2014-11-04 |work=Twitter |publisher=Telltale Games |accessdate=2016-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n''The Wolf Among Us'' has been generally well received by critics and garnered a [[cult following]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.desiblitz.com/content/wolf-among-us-remains-telltales-best-game |title=Why The Wolf Among Us Remains Telltale's Best Game |work=Desiblitz |accessdate=August 13, 2017 }}</ref> In July 2017, Telltale announced that a season 2 of ''The Wolf Among Us'' was scheduled for release in 2018. However, Telltale eventually had to shut down for financial reasons in 2018, with its assets being acquired by [[LCG Entertainment]]. One of the first original games from this new company, [[doing business as]] Telltale Games, will be ''The Wolf Among Us 2'', announced in December 2019.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:TWAU Screenshot.png|thumb|250px|left|In-game conversations are presented in the form of dialogue trees]]\n''The Wolf Among Us'' is a [[graphic adventure game]], played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]].<ref name=\"Gameplanet Review\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Chris |url=http://www.gameplanet.com.au/pc/reviews/g525f3b1c9b3f2/The-Wolf-Among-Us-Episode-1-Faith-review/?referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1: Faith review |date=October 17, 2013 |work=[[Gameplanet]] |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> The player controls protagonist [[Bigby Wolf]], who must investigate the murder of a woman.<ref name=\"PCGamer Preview\">{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Hollander |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/the-wolf-among-us-preview |title=The Wolf Among Us preview |date=August 27, 2013 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> Throughout the game, the player explores various [[3D computer graphics|three-dimensional]] environments, such as apartment buildings and a bar.<ref name=\"TT Review\">{{cite web |last=Gronli |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.technologytell.com/gaming/118966/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-review-bringing-fables-to-life |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1 Review: Bringing Fables to life |date=October 21, 2013 |work=Technology Tell |publisher=NAPCO Media |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> When exploring an environment, the player may find an object they can interact with; when this occurs, they must move a [[Cursor (user interface)|cursor]] over the object to select and examine it.<ref name=\"Polygon Review\">{{cite web |last=McElroy |first=Justin |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/10/10/4824252/fables-the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode One: Faith Review: At The Door |date=October 10, 2013 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> Items of interest are stored in an inventory, and can be used later in the story.<ref name=\"Destructoid Review\"/> The player may also talk with [[non-player character]]s, and see the conversations presented in the form of [[dialogue tree]]s.<ref name=\"Polygon Article\">{{cite web |last=Corriea |first=Alexa Ray |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/4/9/5594270/the-female-gaze-how-being-watched-affects-morality-in-adventure-games |title=The female gaze: how being watched affects your morality in adventure games |date=April 9, 2014 |work=Polygon |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> The dialogue options chosen during conversations would either have a positive or negative effect on how other characters view Bigby, and their perceptions would influence future events in the story.<ref name=\"Destructoid Review\">{{cite web |last=Aziz |first=Hamza |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wolf-among-us-faith-263249.phtml |title=Review: The Wolf Among Us: Faith |date=October 10, 2013 |work=[[Destructoid]] |publisher=Modern Method |accessdate=June 8, 2016 }}</ref> Some scenes are more action-oriented, forcing the player to respond to a series of [[quick time event]] (QTE) prompts.<ref name=\"GameSpot Review\">{{cite web |last=Watters |first=Chris |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-review-testing-my-fait/1900-6415497 |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 Review - Testing My Faith |date=October 21, 2013 |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> The player is not required to complete every QTE prompt, and skipping certain prompts may affect future events in the story.<ref name=\"TouchArcade Review\">{{cite web |last=Leray |first=Joseph |url=http://toucharcade.com/2014/08/25/the-wolf-among-us-review |title='The Wolf Among Us' Review - Red in Tooth and Claw |date=August 25, 2014 |work=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Setting===\n''The Wolf Among Us'' is set in the year 1986, nearly twenty years before the events of ''[[Fables (comics)|Fables]]''.<ref name=\"GameSpot Full Review\">{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Justin |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-wolf-among-us-review/1900-6415981 |title=The Wolf Among Us Review |work=GameSpot |date=December 5, 2014 |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> For years, many of the magical lands described in myth, legend, and folklore (known as The Homelands) have been occupied by an enigmatic tyrant known as the Adversary.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mejia |first=Ozzie |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/81575/the-characters-of-the-wolf-among-us-and-where-the |title=The characters of The Wolf Among Us and where the story may go next |date=October 16, 2013 |work=[[Shacknews]] |publisher=Gamerhub |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> To escape the Adversary's totalitarian regime, many of The Homelands inhabitants fled to [[colonial America]], and created an enclave known as [[Fabletown]], now located in modern-day [[Manhattan]]. To mask their presence from the native humans, all non-human fables have to purchase an enchantment known as a \"glamour\" which allows them to appear human, or be relocated to a rural community known as \"The Farm\".\n\n===Characters===\n{{see also|List of Fables characters}}\nThe protagonist of ''The Wolf Among Us'' is Bigby Wolf ([[Adam Harrington (voice actor)|Adam Harrington]]), formerly the [[Big Bad Wolf]]. He is the sheriff of Fabletown, currently working at the \"Business Office\" under corrupt interim mayor [[Ichabod Crane]] ([[Roger L. Jackson]]), aided by [[Snow White (Fables)|Snow White]] ([[Erin Yvette]]) and the [[Magic Mirror (Snow White)|Magic Mirror]] ([[Gavin Hammon]]) in his investigation along with the help of Bufkin the [[Winged monkeys|winged monkey]] (Chuck Kourouklis) that manages Fabletown's records. Aristocrat [[Bluebeard]] ([[Dave Fennoy]]) also works at the Office though his motives are unclear. Bigby resides at the Woodlands apartments where Colin (Brian Sommer), one of the [[Three Little Pigs]], occasionally crashes at his place. [[Beauty and the Beast]] ([[Melissa Hutchison]] and Gavin Hammon) are also residents of the Woodlands, though currently struggling with a troubled marriage. One of the Fables that Bigby frequently contacts is [[Mr. Toad]] (Chuck Kourouklis) and his son TJ (Toad Jr.), who live in a run-down apartment building nearby.\n\nIn the first episode, the player is introduced to [[Little Red Riding Hood|The Woodsman]] (Adam Harrington), who lives in the same building as Mr. Toad. Standing in Bigby's way are [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee|Dee and Dum Tweedle]] (Gavin Hammon), twin private investigators and criminals. Bigby also encounters Holly (Janet Lipsey), a [[Troll]] who runs the Trip Trap bar, and  barfly [[Grendel]] ([[Kid Beyond]]). The second episode introduces trickster and thief [[Jack Horner (comics)|Jack Horner]] (Colin Benoit), [[Georgie Porgie]] ([[Kevin Howarth]]), a pimp and the owner of the Pudding & Pie strip club, along with prostitute Nerissa (Molly Benson), the former [[The Little Mermaid|Little Mermaid]], Vivian (Sandy Delonga), and [[Clever Hans (fairy tale)|Clever Hans]] (Ben Knoll), the club's bouncer. The third episode introduces the janitor [[Flycatcher (comics)|Flycatcher]] (Dustin Rubin), [[Bloody Mary (folklore)|Bloody Mary]] ([[Kathryn Cressida]]) as a minion of [[There Was a Crooked Man|the Crooked Man]] (Philip Banks), and Aunty Greenleaf ([[Laura Bailey (voice actress)|Laura Bailey]]), a rogue witch who illegally sells cheap black-market glamours to Fables. The fourth episode introduces the [[Jersey Devil]] (Bobby Vickers), the manager of the Lucky Pawn shop and [[Rub-a-dub-dub|Johann the butcher]] ([[Terry McGovern (actor)|Terry McGovern]]), the former owner of the Cut Above butcher shop who has been forced out of his business by the Crooked Man's henchmen.\n\n===Plot===\nThis is a broad overview of the plot. Certain decisions made by the player will alter details of specific events.\n\nBigby Wolf, formerly the Big Bad Wolf, is the Sheriff of Fabletown, a hidden community of fairytale characters located in 1980s New York City. Receiving a call from Mr. Toad, Bigby protects a prostitute from an intoxicated Woodsman. Before she departs, she tells him he is not as bad as everyone says he is.\n\nLater that night, Bigby and Snow White find the woman's head left on the Woodlands doorstep. Clues left with the head identify her as Faith, a Fable from ''[[Allerleirauh]]''. Deputy Mayor Ichabod Crane orders him and Snow to investigate her death. They head to the apartment she shared with her husband Prince Lawrence and find the [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee|Tweedles]], Dee and Dum, snooping through it. They learn that Lawrence and Faith struggled to make ends meet and Faith took up prostitution to help pay the bills. Bigby leaves Snow at the Woodlands while he continues to trace leads. When he returns, he finds the Woodlands surrounded by police, Snow's head sitting on the building's steps.\n\nBigby is taken in for questioning by the mundy police, but Crane uses a spell to wipe the incident from the police's minds. When they return, they are surprised to find Snow still alive; the head is shown to be disguised by a black-market glamour, a spell that non-human Fables use, and belongs instead to a troll named Lily. Bigby tracks Lily's connections to the Pudding & Pie, a strip club run by Georgie Porgie, but Georgie claims innocence. One of his other prostitutes, Nerissa, cryptically directs Bigby to a nearby hotel room. There he finds Lily's blood on the bed, and photographic evidence of Crane engaging in sexual acts with Lily glamoured to look like Snow. He informs Snow of this, and they race back to the Woodlands to find Crane gone, and the Magic Mirror, which could have revealed his location, shattered with one shard missing.\n\nBigby follows a trail of clues to Crane's whereabouts to the apartment of Aunty Greenleaf, one of the witches that makes the black-market glamours. Along the way, Bigby discovers that Crane has been embezzling money from Fabletown over the years to pay off a loan shark known as the Crooked Man. Greenleaf points the two back to the Pudding & Pie. Storming the club, they find Crane trying to extract information out of the prostitutes to prove his innocence. Snow realizes Crane's actions are not that of a murderer, and he is arrested for his embezzlement. Leaving the club, they are attacked by the Crooked Man and his henchmen, the Tweedles and Bloody Mary. Mary and the Tweedles goad Bigby into his werewolf form, and a fight breaks out. When Mary critically wounds Bigby with a silver bullet, Snow steps in to stop the fight and willingly gives up Crane to the Crooked Man to save Bigby's life.\n\nBack at the Woodlands, Bigby struggles to find clues when Nerissa appears. He realizes the ribbon she wears prevents her from speaking the truth, that Faith wore an identical ribbon, and that she died when the ribbon was removed. He follows another trail of clues, and finds evidence of the black-market glamour ring in the Cut Above butcher shop, a pawn shop called the Lucky Pawn where the Crooked Man distributes his loans to Fables owned by Jersey Devil, another henchman of the Crooked Man, and Crane's presence, as well as the missing Mirror Shard. The Mirror reveals Mary putting Crane onto an overseas flight to Paris to keep him from talking, as well as the next location of the door to the Crooked Man's lair, which moves around the city.\n\nBigby enters the Crooked Man's lair alone, meeting him and his agents. The Crooked Man reveals Georgie as Faith and Lily's killer and claims he misunderstood his orders to deal with them, but Georgie asserts the Crooked Man told him to kill the women. A fight ensues and the Crooked Man and a fatally stabbed Georgie escape. When Bigby pursues Georgie and his lover Vivian to the Pudding & Pie, she explains that the Crooked Man and Georgie were acting to stop a plot spearheaded by Faith with the other prostitutes to escape their forced servitude. Vivian is revealed to be the girl with the ribbon around her neck and, having made copies of her ribbon, trapped women like Faith, Lily, and Nerissa for Georgie whilst guaranteeing their silence. Regretting her actions, Vivian undoes her ribbon, breaking the spell but severing her head.\n\nBigby then finds the Crooked Man hiding in an old foundry, and after turning into his true wolf form to kill Bloody Mary, corners him in an office, where he demands a fair trial at the Woodlands. Bigby returns to the Witching Well at the Business Office to recount events to the assembled Fables of the Woodlands, where he and Snow are forced to defend their actions against claims from the Fables. Bigby recounts Vivian's and Georgie's confessions regarding the Crooked Man's involvement, but his word is deemed untrustworthy. Nerissa appears and testifies that she and five other women heard the Crooked Man order the murders. Their testimonies are considered sufficient to believe what Bigby did was right.\n\nIn the epilogue, Snow becomes the new Deputy Mayor and deals with the fallout of the Crooked Man's actions, while Bigby sees off the Fables being taken back to the Farm. Afterward, he encounters Nerissa, who is moving on with her life. She admits that Faith concocted a plan with her and Lily to blackmail Georgie and the Crooked Man for their freedom, using a picture of Lily and Crane together, but Georgie killed the two women when she panicked and revealed their plot to him. Nerissa left Faith's head at the Woodlands to get Bigby involved, and gave false testimony to have the Crooked Man punished, knowing that he was the one who ordered their deaths. Leaving, she comments that Bigby is not as bad as everyone says he is, causing Bigby to recall Faith saying the same before her death. Several past conversations with Faith and Nerissa play out in Bigby's head, leading him to question the true identity of Nerissa.\n\n==Episodes==\nEpisodic releases for the Microsoft Windows, Xbox 360, OS X and PlayStation 3 platforms were released near-simultaneously within the same week; the iOS and PlayStation Vita episodic releases were expected to trail these by about a month or so.\n{{Episode table|background=#142F26|overall=|title=|director=|writer=|airdate=|released=y\n|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = Faith\n |DirectedBy = Nick Herman and Dennis Lenart\n |WrittenBy = Pierre Shorette\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2013|10|11}}\n |ShortSummary = The first murder of a Fable in several years leads Bigby on the trail of a killer.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |Title = Smoke and Mirrors\n |DirectedBy = Jason Latino\n |WrittenBy = [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]], Adam Hines, and Nicole Martinez\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|4}}\n |ShortSummary = Bigby continues investigating for the 'serial killer' walking the streets of Fabletown. He also attempts to find answers from Faith's pimp: Georgie Porgie, and becomes more involved with Beauty and Beast's affairs.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |Title = A Crooked Mile\n |DirectedBy = Martin Montgomery\n |WrittenBy = Adam Hines and Nicole Martinez\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|4|8}}\n |ShortSummary = Following a shocking revelation, Bigby pursues Ichabod Crane, who is now in hiding.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |Title = In Sheep's Clothing\n |DirectedBy = Kent Mudle\n |WrittenBy = Dan Martin\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|5|27}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Kalmari |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/22/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4-release-date-announced |title=The wolf among us episode 4 release date announced |date=2014-05-22 |accessdate=2014-05-22 |publisher=IGN }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Bigby must delve into the criminal underworld to find the Crooked Man.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |Title = Cry Wolf\n |DirectedBy = Vahram Antonian\n |WrittenBy = Nicole Martinez and Adam Hines\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|7|8}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Matulef |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-07-03-the-wolf-among-us-first-season-concludes-next-week |title=The Wolf Among Us' first season concludes next week |date=2014-07-03 |accessdate=2014-07-03 |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Secrets are revealed and decisions are made as Bigby squares off against the Crooked Man, facing off against his deadliest agent, Bloody Mary and learns the full truth about his crimes against Fabletown.\n |LineColor = 142F26\n}}\n}}\n\n==Development==\nIn 2011, [[Telltale Games]] announced that it had acquired licenses to develop video games based on two comic book series, ''[[The Walking Dead (comic book)|The Walking Dead]]'' by [[Robert Kirkman]], and ''[[Fables (comic book)|Fables]]'' by [[Bill Willingham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20110217/telltale-signs-that-videogames-will-be-downloaded-not-sold-at-retail/?mod=ATD_skybox |title=Telltale Signs That Videogames Will Be Downloaded, Not Sold At Retail |date=2011-02-17 |publisher=[[All Things Digital]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2011/07/21/bill-willingham-to-work-on-telltales-fables |title=Bill Willingham to work on Telltale's Fables? |date=2011-02-17 |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref> This announcement came around the same time that the television series [[The Walking Dead (TV series)|''The Walking Dead'']] became critically successful, leading to Telltale to put much of their initial focus on developing ''The Walking Dead'' property through 2011 and 2012.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\">{{cite web |last=Byrne |first=Katherine |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/the-wolf-among-us-was-almost-unshippable-and-could-have-been-a-comedy-says-telltale/0187154 |title=The Wolf Among Us was 'almost unshippable' and could have been a comedy, says Telltale |date=September 18, 2017 |work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] |accessdate=September 18, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921013007/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/the-wolf-among-us-was-almost-unshippable-and-could-have-been-a-comedy-says-telltale/0187154# |archive-date=2017-09-21 }}</ref> This game was released by April 2012, and was a critical success for Telltale. With ''The Walking Dead'' shipping, the company then started working on their ''Fables'' title, but according to Telltale's Job Stauffer, they struggled with the narrative of the title over a year and a half. Stauffer said at one point, they found the game to be more of a comedy, but without much humorous substance and in an un-shippable state.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/> Stauffer said that their team rallied together to refocus the game, delaying it from an early 2012 release<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/02/18/telltales-first-fables-episode-due-in-q1-2012 |title=Telltale's first Fables episode due in Q1 2012 |date=2011-02-18 |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=2012-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017074855/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/02/18/telltales-first-fables-episode-due-in-q1-2012 |archive-date=2013-10-17 }}</ref> to late 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/12/fables-wont-tell-tales-until-q3-2012 |title=Fables won't tell tales until Q3 2012 |date=2012-03-12 |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=2012-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017022435/http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/12/fables-wont-tell-tales-until-q3-2012 |archive-date=2013-10-17 }}</ref> and ultimately to October 2013 when it finally shipped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mixnmojo.com/news/The-Wolf-Among-Us-Reportedly-Delayed-Until-Fall-2013 |title=The Wolf Among Us Reportedly Delayed Until Fall 2013 |date=2013-08-21 |publisher=[[The International House of Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-10-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"polygon pre-order\"/> This did allow for Telltale to incorporate mechanics that had proven successful in ''The Walking Dead'' into their ''Fables'' game.<ref name=\"after TWD\"/>\n\nDue to these delays, Telltale re-announced the ''Fables'' game at the [[New York Comic Con]] in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/telltale-confirms-fables-game-6398311 |title=Telltale Confirms Fables Game |date=2012-10-15 |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref> The name ''The Wolf Among Us'' was revealed in March 2013, and is based on the main character Bigby Wolf.<ref name=\"Fables announcement\"/><ref name=\"after TWD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/12/whats-next-for-telltale-games |title=What's Next for Telltale Games? |date=2013-02-12 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2013-02-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/27/telltales-fables-is-called-the-wolf-among-us |title=Telltale\u2019s Fables is Called The Wolf Among Us |author=Andrew Goldfarb |date=March 27, 2013 |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2019-12-19 |archive-url=https://archive.is/y1NiI |archive-date=2013-08-16 }}</ref>\n\nPre-orders were made available October 3, 2013 from Telltale Games and Steam. Those who pre-ordered through Telltale received a collector's DVD at the end of the season.<ref name=\"polygon pre-order\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/10/3/4801198/the-wolf-among-us-available-for-pre-order-out-this-month |title=The Wolf Among Us available for pre-order, out this month |date=2013-10-03 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2013-10-08 }}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe game was initially released across five episodes between October 2013 and July 2014 for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3, and Xbox 360 platforms.\n\n===Release announcements and dates===\n{{plainlist|\n*On October 8, 2013, it was announced that ''The Wolf Among Us'' would be released on Xbox 360, PC, and Mac worldwide on October 11th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/10/08/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us Episode 1 Release Date Announced |date=2013-10-08 |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref>\n*On October 11, 2013, the digital download released worldwide for [[Xbox 360]], and for [[Microsoft Windows]] from the Telltale Games store.<ref name=\"PC and OS X release\"/> It was also announced that it would release on [[PlayStation 3]] on October 15th in North America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dccomics.com/blog/2018/10/30/the-wolf-among-us-season-premiere-now-available-from-telltale-games-and-dc |title='The Wolf Among Us' Season Premiere Now Available from Telltale Games and DC Entertainment |date=2013-10-11 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref>\n*On October 14, 2013, the digital download released worldwide for [[OS X]] from the Telltale Games store, after fixing an issue with the October 11th release build.<ref name=\"PC and OS X release\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/10/11/the-wolf-among-us-encounters-mac-problems-telltale-working-on-fix.aspx |title=Update: The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 Now Available For Mac |date=2013-10-15 |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=2013-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101075026/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/10/11/the-wolf-among-us-encounters-mac-problems-telltale-working-on-fix.aspx |archive-date=2013-11-01 }}</ref> It also became available through Steam for both PC and Mac.\n*On October 15, 2013, the digital download released on [[PlayStation 3]] in North America<ref name=\"Episode 1\"/> and on October 16, 2013 in Europe and Australia.<ref name=\"PS3PAL\"/>\n*On October 24, 2013, it was announced that it would release on [[iOS]] and [[PlayStation Vita]] in the Fall.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tach |first=Dave |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/10/24/5024832/the-wolf-among-ios-ps-vita |title=The Wolf Among Us headed to iOS and PS Vita this fall |date=2013-10-24 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2014-07-18 }}</ref> The [[iOS]] version was released worldwide on December 4, 2013.<ref name=\"iOS\"/>\n*On February 10, 2014, it was announced that it would release on [[PlayStation Vita]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dunning |first=Jason |url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2014/02/10/playstation-vita-to-get-over-100-games-in-2014 |title=PlayStation Vita to Get \"Over 100 Games\" in 2014: The Wolf Among Us, Invizimals, and More Highlighted |date=February 10, 2014 |work=playstationlifestyle.net |accessdate=April 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n*On May 30, 2014, it was announced that it would release on [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] later that year. Retail versions for [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] were also available for pre-order.<ref>{{cite web |last=Corriea |first=Alexa Rae |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/5/30/5764514/the-walking-dead-wolf-among-us-ps4-xbox-one-telltale-games |title=Telltale's The Walking Dead, The Wolf Among Us coming to PS4 and Xbox One |date=2014-05-30 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=2014-05-30 }}</ref>\n*On November 4, 2014, it released on [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], and [[Xbox One]] in North America and November 7, 2014 in Europe at both retail and digital stores. In addition, the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] retail versions also released on those days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.justpushstart.com/2014/10/wolf-us-ps-vitaps4-release-date-announced |title=The Wolf Among Us PS Vita/PS4 Release Date Announced |date=2014-10-10 |publisher=Just Push Start |accessdate=2019-12-18 }}</ref><ref name=\"xbox1 & ps4\"/>\n}}\n\n===Sequel===\nWhen ''The Wolf Among Us'' was completed by July 2014, Telltale had thought of doing a second season, but they had already committed to the projects leading to ''[[Tales from the Borderlands]]'', ''[[Minecraft: Story Mode]]'', and ''[[Game of Thrones (2014 video game)|Game of Thrones]]''.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/> The company was aware of strong interest in a second season through the intervening years, and they were looking for the right time to develop it.<ref name=\"almost canned, other projects\"/>\n\nA second yet-to-be-named season was announced during the July 2017 [[San Diego Comic Con]], and was originally set to premiere in 2018 for personal computers, consoles, and mobile devices. Both Harrington and Yvette were to return to voice Bigby and Snow White, respectively.<ref name=\"vg247 final season\">{{cite web |last=Nunneley |first=Stephanny |url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/07/19/the-wolf-among-us-2-the-walking-dead-the-final-season-coming-in-2018-batman-the-enemy-within-out-in-august |title=The Wolf Among Us 2, The Walking Dead: The Final Season coming in 2018, Batman: The Enemy Within out in August |date=July 19, 2017 |work=[[VG247]] |accessdate=July 19, 2017 }}</ref> Stauffer said that Season Two would not resolve the apparent cliffhanger related to Nerissa's connection to Faith; he said that it was meant to be ending similar to a [[film noir]] work that made the viewer think about the implications, but never saw this themselves as a cliffhanger. Instead, Season 2 would have continued on with more narrative related to Bigby and Snow White.<ref>{{cite web |last=Purslow |first=Matt |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/the-wolf-among-us/the-wolf-among-us-cliffhanger |title=The Wolf Among Us\u2019s ending is \"absolutely not a cliffhanger\" |date=August 23, 2017 |work=[[PCGamesN]] |accessdate=August 24, 2017 }}</ref>\nBy May 2018, Telltale announced that due to recent internal studio issues, they had to push back the release of the sequel until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last= Kim |first=Matt |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-wolf-among-us-2-delayed-to-2019 |title=The Wolf Among Us 2 Delayed Until 2019 |date=May 25, 2018 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=May 25, 2018 }}</ref> In September 2018, Telltale had a majority studio closure due to \"insurmountable challenges\", cancelling ''The Wolf Among Us''{{' }}s second season among other projects in development.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kim |first=Matt |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/report-telltale-games-shutting-down-the-wolf-among-us-2-and-stranger-things-canceled |title=Sources: Telltale Games Shutting Down, The Wolf Among Us 2 and Stranger Things Canceled [Update, Correction] |date=September 21, 2018 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=September 21, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nUpon Telltale's revival by LCG Entertainment, ''The Wolf Among Us'' was one of the titles reacquired by LCG, but no announcement was made at that time about the sequel.<ref>{{cite web |last=Campbell |first=Colin |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/28/20835854/telltale-games-return-walking-dead-lcg-entertainment |title=Telltale Games is being revived |date=August 28, 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=November 28, 2019 }}</ref> The company announced ''The Wolf Among Us 2'' at [[The Game Awards 2019]]. The sequel will continue events after the first game, though still remain as a prequel to the comic series. The game is being developed in association with [[AdHoc Studio]], formed by former Telltale Games staff, who will focus on the game's narrative and cinematic elements while Telltale will implement the gameplay and other designs. In addition to returning Telltale staff, Harrington and Yvette will return to voice Bigby and Snow White, and Emerson-Johnson will compose music for the game. The game is being developed on the [[Unreal Engine]], and will be released in an episodic approach.<ref>{{cite web |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |\n url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/12/12/telltale-confirms-it-will-make-the-wolf-among-us-2 |title=Telltale confirms it will make The Wolf Among Us 2 |date=\n December 12, 2019 |work=[[Venture Beat]] |accessdate=December 16, 2019 }}</ref> This sequel will be worked completely from scratch, using none of the ideas and initial work that had been done under the former Telltale banner before its closure.<ref>{{cite web |last=Olsen |first=Matthew |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-wolf-among-us-2-is-starting-from-scratch-telltale-confirms |title=The Wolf Among Us 2 is Starting From Scratch, Telltale Confirms |date=December 17, 2019 |work=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=December 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG Series Reviews\n| game1 = The Wolf Among Us\n| mc1 = (PS4) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 80/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us |title=The Wolf Among Us for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref>\n| game2 = Episode 1 \u2013 Faith\n| mc2 = (PS3) 85/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 85/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref><br/>(iOS) 83/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 82/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-1---faith |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 1 - Faith for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 26, 2013 }}</ref>\n| game3 = Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors\n| mc3 = (PS3) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 76/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 73/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/x360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-2---smoke-and-mirrors |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 2 - Smoke and Mirrors for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game4 = Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile\n| mc4 = (PS3) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 77/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-3---a-crooked-mile |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 3 - A Crooked Mile for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 9, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game5 = Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing\n| mc5 = (PC) 75/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(X360) 74/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 69/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-4---in-sheeps-clothing |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 4 - In Sheep's Clothing for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n| game6 = Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf\n| mc6 = (X360) 85/100<ref name=\"MCX360EP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PC) 84/100<ref name=\"MCPCEP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref><br/>(PS3) 75/100<ref name=\"MCPS3EP5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/the-wolf-among-us-episode-5---cry-wolf |title=The Wolf Among Us: Episode 5 - Cry Wolf for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Wolf Among Us'' has received mostly positive reviews from critics. Praise was given to the game's story, action sequences, atmosphere, visual style and faithfulness to the source material while criticism was focused on its pacing and technical issues.\n\n===Episode 1 \u2013 Faith===\n''Episode 1 \u2013 Faith'' received positive reviews from critics. [[Review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]] gave the PlayStation 3 version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP1\"/> the PC version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP1\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 82/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP1\"/>\n\n===Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors===\n''Episode 2 \u2013 Smoke and Mirrors'' received mixed to positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PlayStation 3 version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP2\"/> the PC version 76/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP2\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 73/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP2\"/>\n\n===Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile===\n''Episode 3 \u2013 A Crooked Mile'' received positive reviews. Metacritic gave the PlayStation 3 version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPS3EP3\"/> the PC version 82/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP3\"/> and the Xbox 360 version 77/100.<ref name=\"MCX360EP3\"/>\n\n===Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing===\n''Episode 4 \u2013 In Sheep's Clothing'' received mixed to positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PC version 75/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP4\"/> the Xbox 360 version 74/100,<ref name=\"MCX360EP4\"/> and the PlayStation 3 version 69/100.<ref name=\"MCPS3EP4\"/>\n\n===Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf===\n''Episode 5 \u2013 Cry Wolf'' received positive reviews from critics. Metacritic gave the PC version 84/100,<ref name=\"MCPCEP5\"/> the Xbox 360 version 85/100,<ref name=\"MCX360EP5\"/> and the PlayStation 3 version 75/100.<ref name=\"MCPS3EP5\"/>\n\n===Awards===\nThe series was nominated for Outstanding Achievement in Story and Adventure Game of the Year for the 18th Annual D.I.C.E. Awards by the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interactive.org/images/pdfs/18th-Annual-DICE-Finalists.pdf |title=18th Annual D.I.C.E. Awards Finalists |format=PDF |date=January 14, 2015 |publisher=[[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] |accessdate=January 14, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe series was nominated for two 2014 [[British Academy Games Awards|BAFTA Games Awards]] for Story and Performer (Adam Harrington as Bigby Wolf), losing both to ''[[The Last of Us: Left Behind]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2015/games |title=Games in 2015 - BAFTA Awards |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |accessdate=December 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2014 [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] (NAVGTR) awards the game won ''Direction in a Game Cinema'' and received six nominations: ''Writing in a Drama'' (Pierre Shorette), ''Performance in a Drama, Lead'' ([[Adam Harrington (voice actor)|Adam Harrington]]), ''Original Dramatic Score, Franchise'' (Jared Emerson-Johnson), ''Game, Original Adventure'' (Joe Pinney), ''Camera Direction in a Game Engine'' (Dennis Lenart) and ''Art Direction, Contemporary'' (David Bogan).<ref>{{cite web |title=NAVGTR Awards (2014) |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/2445 |website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers }}</ref>\n\n==Comic adaptation==\nAt the 2014 [[New York Comic Con]], [[Vertigo Comics]] announced that they will be adapting ''The Wolf Among Us'' into comic form, to be released digitally first in December 2014 and later as print comic. The story was adapted for the comic by Lilah Sturges, who has previously written for the ''Fables'' series, and Dave Justus, staying otherwise true to the game's story but exploring some of the characters and back story in more depth.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hennon |first=Blake |url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/fables-the-wolf-among-us-matthew-sturges-dave-justus-on-the-case/#/0 |title=\u2018Fables: The Wolf Among Us': Matthew Sturges, Dave Justus on the case |date=2014-10-10 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2014-10-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Pitts |first=Lan |url=http://www.newsarama.com/22958-fables-the-wolf-among-us-writers-tackle-comic-adaptation-of-game-adaptation-of-comic.html |title= FABLES: THE WOLF AMONG US Writers Tackle Comic Adaptation of Game Adaptation of Comic |date=2014-12-11 |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref> The comic has since been completed.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.telltalegames.com/thewolfamongus/ Telltale's ''The Wolf Among Us'' website]\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Telltale Games}}\n{{Fables}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf Among Us, The}}\n[[Category:2013 video games]]\n[[Category:Detective video games]]\n[[Category:Episodic video games]]\n[[Category:Fables (comics)]]\n[[Category:Interactive movie video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Mystery video games]]\n[[Category:Neo-noir video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Vita games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Telltale Games games]]\n[[Category:Video games with cel-shaded animation]]\n[[Category:Video games based on DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jared Emerson-Johnson]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1986]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Video games about werewolves]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "name_user": "Markovulovic", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wolf_Among_Us"}
{"title_page": "Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma'' (season 5)}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number= 5\n |image        = \n |caption      = \n |country      = Japan\n |num_episodes = 13\n |network      = [[Tokyo MX]], [[Nippon BS Broadcasting|BS11]], [[Animax]], [[AbemaTV]]\n |first_aired  = {{Start date|2020|4|11}}\n |last_aired   = {{End date|present}}\n |episode_list = List of Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma episodes\n |prev_season  = [[Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 4)|Season 4]]\n}}\nThe fifth and last season of ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]'' anime television series, subtitled {{nihongo|''Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma: The Fifth Plate''|\u98df\u621f\u306e\u30bd\u30fc\u30de \u8c6a\u30ce\u76bf|Shokugeki no S\u014dma: Go no Sara}}, was produced by [[J.C.Staff]] and directed by [[Yoshitomo Yonetani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-22/food-wars-shokugeki-no-soma-anime-5th-season-casts-jun-fukuyama/.157797|title=Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma Anime's 5th Season Casts Jun Fukuyama (Updated)|publisher=Anime News Network|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The series was first broadcast in Japan on [[Tokyo MX]]. It premiered on April 11, 2020. The opening theme is \"Last Chapter\" by Nano Ripe, while the ending theme song is \"Crossing Road\" by [[Mai Fuchigami]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-09/nano.ripe-mai-fuchigami-perform-themes-for-food-wars-shokugeki-no-soma-anime-5th-season/.156244 |title=nano.RIPE, Mai Fuchigami Perform Themes for Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma Anime's 5th Season |website=Anime News Network |date=February 9, 2020 |accessdate=February 9, 2020 }}</ref> \n\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n==Episode list==\n<onlyinclude>\n{|class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"width:98%; margin:auto; background:#FFF;\n|- style=\"border-bottom: 3px solid #CCF;\"\n! style=\"width:4em;\"      | {{Abbr|No.|Number}} in ser